1229":"1180–1229","1183–Male":"1183–Afdød","1157–Male":"1157–Afdød","1157":"1157","about 1157":"omkring 1157","1183":"1183","1229":"1229","1180":"1180","France":"Frankrig"},"nl":{"about 1157–Deceased":"circa 1157–Overleden","1180–1229":"1180–1229","1183–Male":"1183–Overleden","1157–Male":"1157–Overleden","1157":"1157","about 1157":"circa 1157","1183":"1183","1229":"1229","1180":"1180","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1157–Deceased":"about 1157–Deceased","1180–1229":"1180–1229","1183–Male":"1183–Deceased","1157–Male":"1157–Deceased","1157":"1157","about 1157":"about 1157","1183":"1183","1229":"1229","1180":"1180","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marc","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Andre, Aurele, Alexandre, Edeline, Lucien, Lucner, Mireille, Pierrot, Renald, Rochenel.","French, Haitian, and Romanian: from the personal name <i>Marc</i> (see   Mark  ).","Breton (mainly Finistère; also <b>Le Marc</b>): from the personal name <i>Marc'h</i>, from Breton <i>marc'h</i> ‘horse’, and probably also from the (French) personal name <i>Marc</i>, which is of Latin origin (see 1 and   Mark  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Marquet","meanings":["French:","habitational name from (Le) Marquet, the name of several places in various parts of France.","from <i>Marquet</i>, a derivative of the personal name   Marc  . It is also found in Germany."]},{"name":"Mark","meanings":["English, Dutch, and Sorbian: from Latin <i>Marcus</i>, the personal name of Saint Mark the Evangelist, author of the second Gospel in the New Testament. This name was also borne by a number of early Christian saints. <i>Marcus</i> is an ancient Roman name, of uncertain (possibly non-Italic) etymology; it may have some connection with the name of the war god <i>Mars</i>; compare   Martin  . The personal name was not as popular in England in the Middle Ages as it was elsewhere in Europe, especially in Italy, where the evangelist became the patron of Venice and the Venetian Republic. He was allegedly buried at Aquileia. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates and similar-sounding names from other languages, e.g. Polish, Czech, and Slovak   Marek  , Ukrainian, Slovenian, Sorbian, Rusyn, and Croatian   Marko  , Greek   Markos  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Jewish and Slavic   Markowicz   and   Markovich  ; see also 6 below.","English and German; Dutch (<b>Van der Mark</b>): topographic name for someone who lived on a boundary between two districts, from Middle English <i>merke</i>, Middle High German <i>marc</i>, Middle Dutch <i>marke</i>, <i>merke</i>, all meaning ‘borderland’. The German term also denotes an area of fenced-off land (see   Marker   5) and, like the English word, is embodied in various placenames which have given rise to habitational names. This surname (in any of the possible senses; see also 5 below) is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine; compare   Marck  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Marck, Pas-de-Calais, France."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mr. Marc was born about 1157, in France. He had at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1157–Deceased":"umbes 1157–Surnud","1180–1229":"1180–1229","1183–Male":"1183–Surnud","1157–Male":"1157–Surnud","1157":"1157","about 1157":"umbes 1157","1183":"1183","1229":"1229","1180":"1180","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1157–Deceased":"noin 1157–Kuollut","1180–1229":"1180–1229","1183–Male":"1183–Kuollut","1157–Male":"1157–Kuollut","1157":"1157","about 1157":"noin 1157","1183":"1183","1229":"1229","1180":"1180","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"about 1157–Deceased":"environ 1157–Décédé","1180–1229":"1180–1229","1183–Male":"1183–Décédé","1157–Male":"1157–Décédé","1157":"1157","about 1157":"environ 1157","1183":"1183","1229":"1229","1180":"1180","France":"France","lifeSummary":"Mr. Marc est né environ 1157, à France. Il a eu au moins 2